Ah, got it! You want the **HTML `<progress>` bar itself** to be red instead of the default blue. âœ…

Hereâ€™s how you can do it:

---

### âœ… **HTML + CSS Example: Red Progress Bar**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<title>Red Progress Bar</title>
<style>
/* Style the progress bar container */
progress {
  width: 300px;
  height: 25px;
  -webkit-appearance: none; /* Remove default styling in Chrome/Safari */
  appearance: none;
}

/* For Firefox */
progress::-moz-progress-bar {
  background-color: #ff4d4d; /* ðŸ”´ red */
}

/* For Chrome, Safari, Edge */
progress::-webkit-progress-bar {
  background-color: #eee; /* light gray background */
}
progress::-webkit-progress-value {
  background-color: #ff4d4d; /* ðŸ”´ red */
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<h3>Uploading Data:</h3>
<progress id="progressBar" value="0" max="100"></progress>
<br><br>
<button onclick="startProgress()">Start Upload</button>

<script>
function startProgress() {
    let progress = document.getElementById("progressBar");
    let value = 0;
    let interval = setInterval(() => {
        if (value >= 100) {
            clearInterval(interval);
            alert("âœ… Upload complete!");
        } else {
            value += 5;
            progress.value = value;
        }
    }, 200);
}
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

---

### âœ… **Notes**

* `::-webkit-progress-value` â†’ sets the filled part of the bar (red here) for Chrome, Safari, Edge.
* `::-moz-progress-bar` â†’ sets the filled part for Firefox.
* `progress::-webkit-progress-bar` â†’ sets the background of the bar (optional light gray).

